x4freetext: PD-300 Neutron Generator
About 8 gram of Nd2O3 powder of natural isotopic
composition (>99.99% pure) was pressed at 10 t/cm2,
and 2.0 cm in diameter was obtained.
The thickness of samples was 1.360 mm, 1.120 mm and
Monitor foils of Nb (99.99% pure, 0.5 mm thick) and Al
(99.999% pure, 0.3 mm thick) of the same diameter as
the pellets were then attached in front and at the
back of each sample.
The groups of samples were placed at 0, 90 and 135 deg
relative to the beam direction and centered about the
T-Ti target at distances of about 5 cm.
Neutrons were produced with an effective
deuteron beam energy of 134 keV and beam current of
The tritium-titanium (T-Ti) target used in the
generator was 2.38 mg/cm2 thick.
A high-purity germanium detector with a
relative efficiency of 68% and an energy resolution
of 1.69 keV at 1332 keV for 60Co.
The distance between the sample and the detector is
about 3-9 cm.
A Au-Si surface barrier detector used in
135 deg accompanying a-particle tube was at a
distance of 110 cm from the target.
Irradiation of the samples was lasted about 2
hours with a yield about 3-4E10 n/(4pi*s).
The cross sections obtained by interpolating the
evaluated values of the literature.
Corrections were made for the self-absorption of the
sample at a given gamma-energy, the coincidence sum
effect of cascade gamma-rays in the investigated
nuclide, and the counting geometry.
Total uncertainty
Counting statistics 0.2-21%
Isotopic abundance about 0.6%
Detector efficiency 2.0-3.0%
Weight of samples 0.1%
Self-absorption of gamma-ray about 0.5%
Relative gamma-ray intensity 1.0-6.7%
Half-life 0.02-1.2%
Coincidence sum effect of cascade
gamma-rays 0-7.5%
Uncertainties of irradiation, cooling
and measuring times 0.1-1.0%
